        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@justinmk I am not talking about opening a file manually, I always use plugins to open files (nvim-tree.lua, telescope.nvim). Both of these plugins have (or had in the past) issues with opening files with parentheses in paths e.g. \"app/(login)/_layout.tsx\".\n\nI would need to dig into the code bases to figure out how they open files. Please lmk if this would help you. But here's a minimal repro:\n\n1. Open nvim without a config\n```\nnvim --clean\n```\n2. Define a test filepath (I used backslashes because windows does. If the answer is \"just don't use backslashes\" or \"just double the number of backslashes\" then idk what to tell you. Isn't the whole idea of `fnameescape()` to escape these special chars?!):\n```\n:let g:test_path = 'app\\(login)\\_layout.tsx'\n```\n3. Notice how fnameescape does not escape the parentheses. Following command results in: `app\\(login)\\_layout.tsx`\n```\n:echo fnameescape(g:test_path)\n```\n\n4. Notice how nvim opens `app(login)\\_layout.tsx` instead of `app\\(login)\\_layout.tsx`\n```\n:execute 'edit ' . fnameescape(g:test_path)\n```\n\nThis can be fixed by adding `(` and `)` to `isfname` to the config like this:\n```lua\nvim.o.isfname = vim.o.isfname .. ',(,)'\n```\nBut I think this workaround causes issues in other areas I have no idea about (see `:h 'isfname'`), which is why it probably isn't inside `isfname` by default.\n\n---\n\nThanks for your ideas, I will see if they work. I have no idea how `:nospecial` is supposed to help though.",
